 {"id": "franken_networkx-ringlabels", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] ring_of_cliques used string node labels like '0_0'; nx uses contiguous integers", "description": "The Rust ring_of_cliques binding emitted nodes as strings ('0_0', '0_1', '1_0', ...), which is a complete labelling divergence from nx's canonical 0..num_cliques*clique_size-1 integer labels. Users comparing edge sets or doing isinstance(n, int) downstream silently broke. Also the error messages for num_cliques<2 / clique_size<2 used internal parameter names rather than nx's human wording. Shadowed the Rust binding with a Python wrapper that mirrors nx's algorithm exactly (combinations over consecutive integer ranges + a bridge edge at i*k+1 to (i+1)*k % total) and uses nx's exact error messages.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T14:45:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T14:45:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T14:45:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Python wrapper mirroring nx", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-bipartiteattr", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] complete_bipartite_graph omitted per-node 'bipartite' attribute + graph name", "description": "nx.complete_bipartite_graph tags the first partition's nodes with ``bipartite=0`` and the second partition's with ``bipartite=1``, and sets ``G.graph['name']='complete_bipartite_graph(n1, n2)'``. These are the protocol keys that nx.algorithms.bipartite consumes to pick a side; without them, downstream bipartite algorithms fall back to heuristics and can produce wrong partitions. The Rust fast path (invoked for integer n1,n2) produced none of these attributes. Always take the Python path so ``bipartite`` + name match nx exactly.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T14:45:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T14:45:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T14:45:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Drop Rust fast path; Python fallback sets attrs", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-sbmrng", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] stochastic_block_model produced different edge sets than nx for same (sizes, p, seed)", "description": "Both fnx's Rust fast path and its Python fallback diverged structurally from nx. On sizes=[3,3] p=[[0.5,0.1],[0.1,0.5]] seed=42 the Rust path gave 2 edges; the Python path gave 5 edges; nx gave 8 edges. nx's sparse-mode sampling uses geometric-skip sampling (log_random / log(1-p) floor) iterated per block pair via combinations_with_replacement, which consumes seed.random() in a specific pattern; fnx's per-node-pair loop consumed seed.random() in a different order. Validate inputs locally with nx's exact messages, then delegate generation to nx and rebuild as an fnx Graph/DiGraph. Verified edge-for-edge parity across sizes [3,3],[5,5,5],[2,2],[10] with various seeds, plus directed mode.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T14:45:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T14:45:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T14:45:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Delegate to nx; local validation preserved", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-convnest", "title": "REVIEW: [MEDIUM] BackendInterface.convert_to_nx didn't recurse into containers with fnx graphs", "description": "nx's backend dispatch protocol calls BackendInterface.convert_to_nx on the result to turn backend types into nx types. fnx's implementation only handled a top-level fnx graph; any dispatched algorithm returning a dict / list / tuple containing fnx.Graph/DiGraph/MultiGraph/MultiDiGraph left the inner graphs as fnx types \u2014 so isinstance(result[k], nx.DiGraph) returned False on those values (fnx.DiGraph is NOT a subclass of nx.DiGraph). Currently no _SUPPORTED_ALGORITHMS returns nested graphs, so this was latent, but the contract violation would surface the moment one was added. Rewrote convert_to_nx to call a new _convert_result_to_nx helper that recursively unwraps fnx graphs inside dict (values), list, tuple; sets are preserved as-is since graphs aren't hashable.", "status": "closed", "priority": 3, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T15:00:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T15:00:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T15:00:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Recursive container unwrap", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
